#Defining a function for plotting bargraph
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
def barplot(data,var,dimens,shape,plot_type,xticks_angle,title,plot_lables):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    dims = (dimens[0], dimens[1])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=dims)
    sb.set_style('darkgrid')
    if plot_type.lower() == "u":
        if shape.lower() == "v":
            sb.countplot(data=data, x=var[0],ax = ax, color = base_color).set(title=title)
        else:
            sb.countplot(data=data, y=var[0],ax = ax, color = base_color).set(title=title)
    elif plot_type.lower() == "b":
        if shape.lower() == "v":
            sb.barplot(data=data, x=var[0],y=var[1],color=base_color).set(title=title)
        else:
            sb.barplot(data=data, x=var[1],y=var[0],color=base_color).set(title=title)
        
    plt.xlabel(plot_lables[0]);
    plt.ylabel(plot_lables[1]);
    plt.xticks(rotation = xticks_angle)
    plt.show()

# Creating a function with log scale
def hist(var,xlabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=[12, 6.5])
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.2, np.log10(flightsDF[var].max())+0.02, 0.02)
    plt.hist(data = flightsDF, x = var , bins = bins)
    plt.xscale('log')
    plt.xticks([300,500, 1e3, 2e3], [300,500, '1k', '2k'])
    plt.xlabel(xlabel);

def plot(data,cols,kind,figprams, labels,title):
    data.plot(x=cols[0], y=cols[1], kind=kind, figsize=(figprams[0],figprams[1]))
    plt.xlabel(labels[0])
    plt.ylabel(labels[1])
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()
In [128]:
#Defining function for data aggregation
def aggregateData(dataFrame,xCol,yCol):
    years = dataFrame[xCol].unique()
    countByYear = []
    for year in years:
        year_df = dataFrame[dataFrame[xCol]==year] 
        count = len(year_df.index) 
        countByYear.append((year, count))
    countByYearDF = pd.DataFrame(countByYear, columns=[xCol,yCol]).sort_values(xCol).reset_index().drop(['index'], axis=1)
    return countByYearDF
In [129]:
#Defining function for creating subplots
def subplotsDiffData(data1,data2,kinds,plot1labels,plot2labels):
    #Subplots for 
    fig = plt.figure() # create figure
    ax0 = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1) 
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2) 
    # Subplot 1: Box plot
    data1.plot(x=plot1labels[0], y=plot1labels[1],kind=kinds[0], figsize=(20, 6), ax=ax0) # add to subplot 1
    ax0.set_title('')
    ax0.set_xlabel(plot1labels[0])
    ax0.set_ylabel(plot1labels[1])
    # Subplot 2: Line plot
    data2.plot(x=plot2labels[0], y=plot2labels[1],kind=kinds[1], figsize=(20, 6), ax=ax1) # add to subplot 2
    ax1.set_title ('')
    ax1.set_xlabel(plot2labels[0])
    ax1.set_ylabel(plot2labels[1])
    plt.show()

#Defining function for creating subplots
def subplots(data,kinds,plot1labes,plot2labels):
    #Subplots for 
    fig = plt.figure() # create figure
    ax0 = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1) 
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2) 
    # Subplot 1: Box plot
    data.plot(kind=kinds[0], color='blue', vert=False, figsize=(20, 6), ax=ax0) # add to subplot 1
    ax0.set_title('')
    ax0.set_xlabel(plot1labes[0])
    ax0.set_ylabel(plot1labes[1])
    # Subplot 2: Line plot
    data.plot(kind=kinds[1], figsize=(20, 6), ax=ax1) # add to subplot 2
    ax1.set_title ('')
    ax1.set_ylabel(plot2labels[0])
    ax1.set_xlabel(plot2labels[1])
    plt.show()

Conclusions¶

It is very clear that there is a strong relationship between Arrival Delay and Depature delay. And when it comes to travelling the best month for travelling is February becauses it has lowest number of delays compared to other months. The month of August is not very good for travel as it has the highest number of delays Weather is the main cause for most cancellations it might be a good idea to check weather when planning to travel to avoid frustrations.
